<article>
    <h1>Nor&#xAD;we&#xAD;gian de&#xAD;signer fas&#xAD;ci&#xAD;nated by batik</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200807/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-07"><time>2020-08-07</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE STYLE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Mette Hart­man’s pieces are painstak­ingly hand-drawn on silk by batik-mak­ers in Java, In­done­sia, so you will never find two of the same pieces.</p>
    <p>Only one 2m-long piece of fab­ric is made out of each de­sign, then flown to Sin­ga­pore to be tai­lored into a cloth­ing item for her lux­ury re­sortwear la­bel Martha Who.</p>
    <p>“It was hard to find batik-mak­ers who would work with silk,” says the 55-year-old Nor­we­gian de­signer, who started her slow-fash­ion la­bel six years ago af­ter mov­ing here in 2008.</p>
    <p>She came across the batik­mak­ers in Java when she was trav­el­ling around South-east Asia.</p>
    <p>Even be­fore com­ing to Asia, she had “a pas­sion­ate love of tex­tiles”, run­ning fash­ion stores in Europe and sell­ing batik scarves to a se­lect clien­tele. “I’m just very pas­sion­ate about batik. I think it’s very beau­ti­ful and these old tech­niques are im­por­tant,” she adds.</p>
    <p>For Sin­ga­pore Sto­ries, she in­tends to hon­our more of such old tech­niques, in line with the rein­ter­pre­ta­tion of the past.</p>
    <p>Tak­ing in­spi­ra­tion from the Sin­ga­pore Botanic Gar­dens, her de­signs fea­ture mo­tifs of or­chids, birds and ponds on floaty kaf­tans.</p>
    <p>They are de­signed for a “tea party in the Botanic Gar­dens” – with a cor­re­spond­ing blue-and-white pal­ette to mimic Per­anakan Chi­nese porce­lain teaware.</p>
    <p>Her la­bel’s pieces, which are stocked at De­sign Or­chard, of­ten mix prints – tra­di­tional with ab­stract; Sin­ga­porean and Swedish mo­tifs; and var­i­ous craft tech­niques.</p>
    <p>The de­signer, who has been up­cy­cling ex­cess silk fab­rics into re­us­able face masks, hopes to ex­pand her on­line reach. She adds: “I will use this com­pe­ti­tion as a spring­board to fur­ther de­velop and pre­serve tra­di­tional de­signs for a mod­ern take, to make it ac­ces­si­ble for my cus­tomers.”</p>

